 <main class="flex-grow max-w-6xl mx-auto mt-[60px]">
	<p class="text-black mb-5">Feedback is part of everyday work. We give it in meetings, in project reviews, during coaching, and in quick conversations with colleagues. When feedback is done well, it helps people improve, grow, and work better together. When it is done badly, it can feel vague, personal, or discouraging.</p>

<p class="text-black">In this lesson, you will look at what makes feedback genuinely helpful and how to recognise the difference between useful feedback and unhelpful criticism.</p>

<h1 class="mb-5 text-4xl font-bold">Why feedback matters</h1>
<p>Good feedback helps people understand what is working, what needs to change, and what they can do next. It creates clarity. It supports learning. It can also build trust when it is shared respectfully and with the right intention.

In healthy teams, feedback is not only about correcting mistakes. It is also about recognising strengths, encouraging progress, and helping people perform at their best.

Poor feedback, on the other hand, often creates confusion. People may leave the conversation unsure of what they did wrong or what they should do differently. In some cases, badly delivered feedback can make people defensive or less confident.</p>

<div role="alert" class="alert">
